iOne of the most famous features of NixOS is that most software		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iconfigurations on the system are generated and managed exclusively by		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ia Nix-language config file. Even if such software modifies its config		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifile while running, the config file will still be overwritten on the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
inext Nix config switch or the next reboot.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFor example, if you run `ls -alh /etc` on a computer running NixOS,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iyou can observe that most config files are simply soft links to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`/etc/static`:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i# Unrelated lines omitted		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilrwxrwxrwx  1 root root     18 Jan 13 03:02 bashrc -> /etc/static/bashrc		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilrwxrwxrwx  1 root root     18 Jan 13 03:02 dbus-1 -> /etc/static/dbus-1		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilrwxrwxrwx  1 root root     17 Jan 13 03:02 fonts -> /etc/static/fonts		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilrwxrwxrwx  1 root root     17 Jan 13 03:02 fstab -> /etc/static/fstab		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilrwxrwxrwx  1 root root     21 Jan 13 03:02 fuse.conf -> /etc/static/fuse.conf		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i-rw-r--r--  1 root root    913 Jan 13 03:02 group		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilrwxrwxrwx  1 root root     21 Jan 13 03:02 host.conf -> /etc/static/host.conf		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilrwxrwxrwx  1 root root     18 Jan 13 03:02 hostid -> /etc/static/hostid		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilrwxrwxrwx  1 root root     20 Jan 13 03:02 hostname -> /etc/static/hostname		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilrwxrwxrwx  1 root root     17 Jan 13 03:02 hosts -> /etc/static/hosts		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i# ...		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`/etc/static` itself, by the way, is linked to `/nix/store` and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imanaged by NixOS:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilrwxrwxrwx 1 root root 51 Jan 13 03:02 /etc/static -> /nix/store/41plm7py84sp29w3bg4ahb41dpfxwf9l-etc/etc		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHere's the question: is it really necessary to store the contents of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`/etc` on the disk drive? They're going to be regenerated on each		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ireboot or config switch anyway.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSimilarly, it seems that most files on the NixOS root partition can be		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
igenerated with the config file:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/bin` folder only contains `/bin/sh`, which is soft linked to Bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  in `/nix/store`;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/etc` folder contains mostly files managed by NixOS;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/usr` folder only contains `/usr/bin/env`, which is soft linked to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Coreutils in `/nix/store`;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/mnt` and `/srv` are empty by default;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - And instead of actual data, `/mnt` is usually used to store mount		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    points for other partitions.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/dev`, `/proc` and `/sys` are virtual folders that store the state		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  of hardware devices and the system itself;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/run` and `/tmp` are RAM-backed storages for temporary files.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Note: Nix Daemon stores its temporary files under `/tmp` while		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    packaging. If `/tmp` is backed by RAM, the system may run out of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    memory while building large packages (such as the Linux kernel).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    Therefore, `/tmp` in NixOS is **NOT BACKED BY RAM BY DEFAULT**,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    and needs to be enabled with `boot.tmpOnTmpfs = true;`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iExcluding these folders, only a few folders store data that actually		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ineed preserving on disk:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/boot` for the bootloader;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/home` and `/root` for home directories of users;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/nix` for all packages of NixOS;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/var` for data files of system-level software.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIn fact, NixOS itself only requires `/boot` and `/nix` to boot. The		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iISO downloaded from the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[Official NixOS download page](https://nixos.org/download.html)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icontains, in addition to the ISOLinux bootloader, only a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`nix-store.squashfs` containing data in `/nix/store`:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
