iThen, is it possible to modify NixOS to mimic the behavior of the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iinstallation ISO, and only save the necessary folders of `/boot`,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`/home`, `/nix`, `/root`, `/var` to disk? Or to put it in a direct		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iway, is it possible to set the root directory `/` backed by RAM, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imount these folders to their expected locations?		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe answer is yes, and there's no modification needed. Except mounting		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`nix-store.squashfs`, the NixOS on installation ISO uses the exact		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isame boot sequence as a regular NixOS on hard drive.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Pros for going "Stateless"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iCompared to a regular NixOS, such a "stateless" NixOS only stores the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i"states" you designated onto your disk. Such state may contain files		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iof your website, contents of your database, or browsing history of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iyour browser. The rest of the states, which you did not designate to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isave, are discarded upon reboot.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThis is the most significant "pro" for such a configuration: you only		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipreserve the states you want.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- If some software secretly changes its config file, or stores its		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  data on a different location, such modifications are lost on reboot,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  and the software's configuration will be exactly the same as the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  expected value in your Nix-language config file.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- There will be no left over config files in your `/etc` folder. They		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  are gone on the next reboot.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- You only need to backup those states not managed by Nix (such as		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  `/home`, `/root` and `/var`), in addition to the Nix-language config		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  file, to ensure that you can restore the system to the exact state.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Since most files in the root directory are soft links generated		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  according to the config file, it takes almost no space. On one of my		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  servers, the root directory takes as small as 660KB of space:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i# sudo du -h -d1 -x /		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i0       /srv		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i0       /mnt		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i0       /usr		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i0       /bin		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i0       /home		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i572K    /root		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i0       /tmp		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i84K     /etc		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i4.0K    /var		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i660K    /		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Preparation		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTo set up a NixOS following steps in this post, you need to prepare:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. A NixOS installation, managing its configuration with Flake.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. A LiveCD of NixOS or any other Linux distro, since we need to move		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   critical files of NixOS.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Convert Root to RAM Drive		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWith a regular NixOS installation, you usually have a config entry for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe root partition similar to this:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifileSystems."/" = {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  device = "/dev/vda1";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  fsType = "btrfs";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  options = [ "compress-force=zstd" ];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i};		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i# You may also mounted other partitions, like /boot		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifileSystems."/boot" = {};		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe most important folder for NixOS is `/nix`, so we change the root		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifolder `/` to a RAM drive `tmpfs`, and mount the original partition		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ionto `/nix`:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifileSystems."/" = {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  device = "tmpfs";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  fsType = "tmpfs";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # You must set mode=755. The default is 777, and OpenSSH will complain and disallow logins		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  options = [ "relatime" "mode=755" ];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i};		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifileSystems."/nix" = {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  device = "/dev/vda1";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  fsType = "btrfs";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  options = [ "compress-force=zstd" ];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i};		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i# No need to change config for other partitions		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifileSystems."/boot" = {};		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTheoretically, if you apply this config, shutdown, move the files to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe correct location in LiveCD, you will get a NixOS that **only		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipersists whatever is in your Nix configuration**. This is good for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iusing temporarily (like the NixOS installation ISO), but since other		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iimportant states not managed by Nix is not persisted, this is not		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iideal for everyday usage.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSuch important states not preserved include:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/etc/machine-id`, random ID generated by SystemD, used for log		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  management		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/etc/NetworkManager/system-connections`, connections stored by		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Network Manager		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key.pub`, OpenSSH public key		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/etc/ssh/ssh_host_rsa_key.pub`, OpenSSH public key		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key`, OpenSSH private key		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- `/etc/ssh/ssh_host_rsa_key`, OpenSSH private key		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- and data files in `/home`, `/root`, `/var`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOur next step is to add rules for each of these files/folders, to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipersist them on disk.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Persisting Important State Files		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince `/nix` partition is already mounted, I elected to store the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istates in `/nix/persistent`. You can store them on another partition		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iat your discretion.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThen, use bind mounts to map the files back to where they should be:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifileSystems."/etc/machine-id" = {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  device = "/nix/persistent/etc/machine-id";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  options = [ "bind" ];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i};		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i# ...		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you need to persist lots of files, you need one mount for each file		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ior folder, which is cumbersome and error-prone. The good news is that		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe Nix community provided a NixOS module		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[Impermanence](https://github.com/nix-community/impermanence) for such		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iscenario, which provides a convenient way to map files to another		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilocation.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFirst, add Impermanence to `inputs` in your `flake.nix`:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i{		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  inputs = {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    impermanence.url = "github:nix-community/impermanence";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i}		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThen add Impermanence to the module list of NixOS:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i{		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  outputs = { self, nixpkgs, ... }@inputs: {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    nixosConfigurations."nixos" = nixpkgs.lib.nixosSystem {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      system = "x86_64-linux";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      modules = [		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        # Add the following line		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        inputs.impermanence.nixosModules.impermanence		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        ./configuration.nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      ];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i}		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iYou will be able to map files in batch with the following format, no		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilonger needing a lot of mounts in `fileSystems`:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i# /nix/persistent is the location you plan to store the files		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ienvironment.persistence."/nix/persistent" = {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Hide these mount from the sidebar of file managers		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  hideMounts = true;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Folders you want to map		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  directories = [		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    "/etc/NetworkManager/system-connections"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    "/home"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    "/root"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    "/var"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Files you want to map		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  files = [		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    "/etc/machine-id"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    "/etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key.pub"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
