i## Move Temp Directory of Nix Daemon		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNix Daemon stores its temporary files under `/tmp` while packaging. If		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`/tmp` is backed by RAM, the system may run out of memory while		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibuilding large packages (such as the Linux kernel).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`/tmp` in NixOS is not backed by RAM by default, but with our		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iconfiguration, `/tmp` will be placed on root folder's RAM drive.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTherefore, we can move Nix Daemon's temp files onto the disk. I'm		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imoving it to `/var/cache/nix` for example:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isystemd.services.nix-daemon = {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  environment = {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    # Location for temporary files		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    TMPDIR = "/var/cache/nix";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  serviceConfig = {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    # Create /var/cache/nix automatically on Nix Daemon start		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    CacheDirectory = "nix";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i};		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, this option does not apply to the root user. This is caused		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iby the nix command handling the build request itself under root user,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irather than passing it to the Nix Daemon. Therefore, we need to add an		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ienvironment variable `NIX_REMOTE=daemon`, to force the nix command to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icall the daemon:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ienvironment.variables.NIX_REMOTE = "daemon";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> Thanks for NixOS CN Telegram group user "洗白白" for pointing out		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> the problem, and "Nick Cao" for providing a fix.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Activate Config		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWith the configuration complete, it's finally time to activate it.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFirst, run `sudo nixos-rebuild boot --flake .` to activate the config		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ion next reboot. Remember not to use		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`sudo nixos-rebuild switch --flake .`, since we need to move the files		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito their correct locations in LiveCD before we can use that config.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iReboot the computer into the LiveCD, and mount and `cd` into the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ioriginal root partition:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- **BACK UP YOUR DATA if you're unfamiliar with the process!**		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Create a `persistent` folder, correspondong to `/nix/persistent`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  after system starts;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Move all preserved paths listed above into the `persistent` folder;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Remove all folders except `nix` and `persistent`;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - **BACK UP YOUR DATA BEFORE REMOVAL!**		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Move all folders in `nix` to the current directory;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Finally, remove the `nix` directory and reboot.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you did everything correctly, you will boot into a "stateless"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNixOS. Everything you elected to persist will be mounted back to their		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ioriginal location, so the system should behave exactly the same.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, your root partition has become a `tmpfs` RAM disk, all states		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iyou don't intend to keep will disappear after a reboot, and you will		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iget a "brand new" operating system each time you start your computer.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
